        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2015_Solutions_2015s_page_005_9",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "for some r, s. If s = 0, then clearly all powers of M are in xS. Also, if r = 0, then one easily checks that M3 is in S.",
        "bbox": [
          0.556078431372549,
          0.13515151515151516,
          0.9192156862745098,
          0.1787878787878788
        ],
        "order": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2015_Solutions_2015s_page_005_10",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "We now assume rs ≠ 0, and show that in that case M cannot be in S. First, note that the characteristic polyno- mial of M is x2 − 2rx − 8s2, and since M is nonsingular (as s ≠ 0), this is also the minimal polynomial of M by the Cayley-Hamilton theorem. By repeatedly using the relation M2 = 2rM + 8s2I, we see that for each positive integer, we have Mk = tkM + ukI for unique real con- stants tk, uk (uniqueness follows from the independence of M and I). Since M is in S, we see that Mk lies in S only if uk = 0.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5568627450980392,
          0.18363636363636363,
          0.92,
          0.3290909090909091
        ],
        "order": 4
      }
    ]
  },
  {
